--- title: Design Contract --- # Design Contract This contract applies to `Pathogen::*` components, Lookbook previews,
and host application usage. It does not replace feature-level UI specs. Feature specs should cite this contract, follow
it by default, and document local exceptions with a short rationale. ## Ownership - `Pathogen::*` components are the
shared cross-project design-system surface. - Host applications may keep local components for product-specific needs,
but new reusable UI should be considered for Pathogen first. - Existing host components should conform to Pathogen
tokens and accessibility rules when they remain in use. - Lookbook previews should demonstrate the same product
environment host apps should build. ## Aesthetic Pathogen should read as a clinical enterprise data tool: compact,
precise, accessible, and quiet. Use restrained systems such as GitHub, dense Linear product surfaces, and public-sector
utility design as closer references than expressive brand sites. Avoid large decorative gradients, oversized cards,
heavy shadows, and marketing-page composition in component examples. ## Typography - Use the Pathogen sans stack by
default. - Body text and descriptions should usually be `text-sm` or `text-base`. - Labels use `text-sm font-semibold`
when they identify a setting, row, or control. - Muted copy uses neutral muted text. - Page headings are
component-owned. Host pages should not override heading size or weight on shared heading components. - Keep weights
restrained. Prefer normal body text and semibold labels/headings before adding new weights. - Avoid decorative display
typography in product surfaces. ## Spacing, Radius, And Surfaces - Prefer Tailwind's default 4px spacing rhythm:
`gap-1`, `gap-2`, `gap-4`, `gap-6`, and `gap-8`. - Card and panel surfaces use a neutral background, a 1px neutral
border, and a small radius. - Form primitives can use `rounded-sm`; most controls and panels should converge around
`rounded-md` or `rounded-lg`. - Product UI should be mostly flat. Use shadows primarily for overlays, tooltips,
popovers, and menus. - Do not add page-specific spacing tokens unless a component needs to absorb the pattern. ## Colour
- Pathogen owns semantic tokens. Host applications own brand mapping. - Keep the public `--color-primary-*` override
contract. - Use primary/accent roles for the main brand/action scale. - Use neutral/surface roles for surfaces, borders,
body text, muted text, and dark-mode neutrals. - Components should avoid hard-coded host brand colours. - Status colours
must carry status meaning: danger, warning, success, or info. ## Focus And Keyboard Access Focus must be visible in
light mode, dark mode, and high-contrast modes. - Components must expose a visible `focus-visible` outline or equivalent
focused state. - Do not rely on transparent borders to hide focus or state. Forced-colours modes may render them
visibly. - Keyboard interaction should use native controls first. - Custom controls must preserve expected keyboard
behaviour. - Dense widgets such as data grids must keep active, focus, selected, disabled, and hover states visually
distinct. ## Controls Controls should communicate state by more than colour. Switches: - Use a native checkbox with
`role="switch"`. - The accessible name should be the visible setting name only. - Use `aria-describedby` for
descriptions and row status when present. - Show visible `On` / `Off` text and mark it `aria-hidden="true"` to avoid
duplicate state announcements. - Communicate state through colour, thumb position, and visible state text. - Use
reduced-motion-safe thumb animation. - Include forced-colours support for track, thumb, checked state, and focus
outline. - Do not make an entire settings row clickable unless the row is itself the control. Forms: - Labels should be
visible and programmatically associated with controls. - Help text should use muted neutral text and remain close to the
control it describes. - Disabled controls must be visually muted and use disabled cursor/opacity states. ## Async
Feedback Inline asynchronous actions should keep users oriented. - Prefer row-scoped feedback for row-scoped actions. -
Use visible `Saving...`, `Saved`, and error text when the result affects the current row. - Avoid global flashes for
small inline control updates. - When Turbo or a similar mechanism replaces a row, preserve or restore focus to the
initiating control. - Use persistent live regions outside replaceable fragments when announcements must survive DOM
replacement. - Render failed saves from canonical persisted state so the UI does not show an unsaved optimistic state.
## Empty States - Use concise headings and calm body copy. - Add an action only when users have a useful action to take.
- Icons are optional. If used, they should be subdued and decorative unless they add meaning. ## Copy Tone - Use calm,
declarative copy. - Prefer plain settings and workflow language over marketing language. - Feature names should be nouns
or noun phrases, not imperatives. - Avoid alarming language for experimental or changing features. - Do not add phrases
such as "enable or disable" to a switch's accessible name when role and state already communicate that. ## Accessibility
Baseline Shared components must meet these expectations: - Semantic HTML first. - WCAG AA contrast for text and
meaningful UI state. - Visible keyboard focus. - Screen-reader names, descriptions, and statuses that match the visible
UI. - Reduced-motion handling for non-essential animation. - Forced-colours/high-contrast support for custom controls. -
State must not be communicated by colour alone.
